The fundamental attribution error is when people have a tendency to explain the behavior of others in terms of internal dispositions or personality traits, while they explain their own behavior in terms of external factors or situational variables. This is referred to as the fundamental attribution error. There are three explanations on why this occurrence takes place: People have a tendency to regard their own conduct as being more impacted by situational conditions, but they view the behavior of others as being more influenced by their underlying inclinations. This is an example of the self-serving bias. This is due to the fact that it is more beneficial to one's own self-interest to regard one's own conduct as being driven by other causes, since this releases one from the responsibility of their actions. Information that is scarce: People often have limited knowledge about the context and circumstances surrounding the actions of others, which may cause them to make assumptions about the person's fundamental dispositions. This can lead to misunderstandings and miscommunications. People have a tendency to focus on information that confirms their already held beliefs and attitudes about other people. This can lead them to view the behavior of others as a reflection of their inherent dispositions rather than considering the factors that are present in the situation. This bias is known as confirmation bias. People have a tendency to explain the behavior of others in terms of internal dispositions, while explaining their own behavior in terms of external factors. This can be due to self-serving bias, limited information, or confirmation bias. In conclusion, the fundamental attribution error refers to the tendency of people to attribute the behavior of others to internal dispositions. 